= Martial Law

Papen continues to assert his independence, disregarding Schleicher’s advice, and is still planning to declare martial law, dissolve the Reichstag, and cancel elections indefinitely when the Reichstag reconvenes this week, as he announced to the cabinet. His aim is to implement a new constitution via plebiscite—or, perhaps, simply through a presidential decree, with Hindenburg’s continued support.

Amid rising labor protests and growing hostility from all corners of German society, Schleicher can no longer support his former ally. Papen’s reckless pursuit of political suicide, backed only by President Hindenburg, has pushed Schleicher to distance himself from Papen’s unpopular policies in preparation for his own chancellorship. He has engaged with trade unions and a variety of political figures, including Gregor Strasser, to build the necessary support.

One thing is clear: Papen must go for German democracy to survive.

