An embittered Papen—convinced that Schleicher orchestrated his downfall and vowing never to forgive the betrayal—has officially submitted his resignation to Hindenburg, who, with reluctance, has accepted it. 

As this marks yet another cabinet's fall under Schleicher's influence, Hindenburg's suspicions of his motives begin to grow, particularly with Schleicher’s constant invoking of national security as justification for his actions.

