Schleicher is now Papen’s successor, having orchestrated his downfall through manipulated war games conducted by his close friends, and has been appointed chancellor with full support from President Hindenburg.

However, Schleicher is deeply reluctant to accept the position. He prefers to exert influence through his extensive behind-the-scenes network, knowing full well that he lacks the public profile and charisma necessary to be an effective chancellor. Despite his reservations, Schleicher feels bound by duty to obey a direct order from the commander-in-chief.

His appointment is a breath of fresh air compared to Papen, and his more moderate and social leanings are more acceptable to the <span style="color: #c00000;">**SPD**</span> and the party system as a whole.

However, many still view Schleicher as little better than his predecessor. After all, he was responsible for the [? if otl_prussian_coup_seen:&nbsp;Prussian coup and the?] disastrous policies of the Papen government. At the end of the day, most folk view him as just another <span style="color: #808080;">reactionary</span>.